AB  - This study investigates how successful Russian Internet Research Agency (IRA) Twitter accounts constructed the followings that were central to their disinformation campaigns around the 2016 U.S. presidential election. Treating an accountâ€™s social media following as both an ego network and an audience critical for information diffusion and influence accrual, we situate IRA Twitter accountsâ€™ accumulation of followers in the ideologically polarized, attention driven, and asymmetric political communication system. Results show that partisan enclaves on Twitter contributed to IRA accountsâ€™ followings through retweeting; and that mainstream and hyperpartisan media assisted conservative IRA accountsâ€™ following gain by embedding their tweets in news. These results illustrate how network dynamics within social media and news media amplification beyond it together boosted social media followings. Our results also highlight the dynamics fanning the flames of disinformation: partisan polarization, media fragmentation and asymmetry, and an attention economy optimized for engagement rather than accuracy. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2023 APA, all rights reserved) (Source: journal abstract)
