AB  - This work studies the use of disinformation to construct an image of otherness through the internet. We applied a content analysis methodology to the 161 racist, xenophobic or Islamophobic fake news pieces that were discredited in 2020 by the four Spanish information verification media entities accredited by the International Fact-Checking Network: Maldita.es, Newtral, Efe Verifica and Verificat. The results show that the most commonly used formats were image and video, that disinformation was most often based on taking information out of context and deception, and that the source could not be identified. The most shared characteristics associated otherness with receiving aid, violence and illegal immigration. The most commonly used images were photographs, which mostly showed people in a general manner (not individually). Despite this, disinformation was not generated by manipulating images, but by inserting text over images. The use of supposed screenshots to create fictitious references or take truthful screenshots out of context was also notable.Alternate abstract:Este trabajo estudia la construcciÃ³n de la imagen de la otredad a travÃ©s de la desinformaciÃ³n en Internet. Para ello, aplica una metodologÃ­a de anÃ¡lisis de contenido a los 161 bulos de carÃ¡cter racista, xenÃ³fobo o islamÃ³fobo desmentidos en 2020 por los cuatro medios espaÃ±oles de verificaciÃ³n de informaciÃ³n acreditados por la International Fact-Checking Network: Maldita.es, Newtral, Efe Verifica y Verificat. Los resultados evidencian que los formatos mÃ¡s empleados fueron la imagen y el vÃ­deo, y que las desinformaciones se basaron mayoritariamente en la descontextualizaciÃ³n y el engaÃ±o, sin identificar su fuente. Los atributos mÃ¡s transmitidos asociaron la otredad a la recepciÃ³n de ayudas, la violencia y la inmigraciÃ³n irregular. Las imÃ¡genes mÃ¡s empleadas fueron las fotografÃ­as, que mayoritariamente representaron a las personas de manera no individualizada; sin embargo, la des